### Plot likelihood function of alpha and beta
gamma.log.likelihood <- function(alpha,beta,data=prof.salary.trans){
  n <- length(data)
  fac1 <- n*alpha*log(beta)
  fac2 <- -n*lgamma(alpha)
  fac3 <- (alpha-1)*sum(sapply(data,log))
  fac4 <- -beta*sum(data)
  return(fac1+fac2+fac3+fac4)
}
aa.shape <- seq(0.1, 100, 1)
bb.scale <- seq(0.1, 100, 1)
ll <- outer(aa.shape, bb.scale, 
            FUN=function(a,b){gamma.log.likelihood(a,b)})
contour(x = aa.shape, y = bb.scale, z = ll, nlevels = 150, xlab = "alpha", 
    ylab = "beta", main = "Log-Likelihood Contours of Transformed Data")
abline(a = -2, b = 0.5, lty=2, col="blue")
abline(a = 8, b = 0.5, lty=2, col="blue")

### Find MLE of alpha and beta
neg.gamma.log.likelihood <- function(theta){
  return(-gamma.log.likelihood(theta[1], theta[2]))
}
theta.hat <- optim(c(1,1), neg.gamma.log.likelihood)$par # the MLE

fisher.inf <- function(x = NULL, shape = NULL, scale = NULL) {
    n = length(x)
    val = matrix(0, ncol = 2, nrow = 2)
    val[1, 1] = n * trigamma(shape)
    val[2, 2] = n * shape/scale^2
    
    val[1, 2] = n/scale
    val[2, 1] = n/scale
    
    return(val)
}
evalquad <- function(x1 = NULL, x2 = NULL, xstar = NULL, A = NULL) {
    # returns a matrix of quadratic forms evaluates for every x1 and x2.
    # (c(x1,x2) - xstar) A (c(x1,x2) - xstar)
    
    val = matrix(0, nrow = length(x1), ncol = length(x2))
    for (j in 1:length(x2)) {
        val[, j] = mahalanobis(x = cbind(x1, x2[j]), center = xstar, cov = A, 
            inverted = TRUE)
    }
    return(val)
}

### Log-likelihood ratio statistic
gamma.logLikeRatio <- function(theta, mle){
  l.tilde <- gamma.log.likelihood(mle[1], mle[2])
  l <- gamma.log.likelihood(theta[1], theta[2])
  return(2*(l.tilde-l))
}

### Results from the frequentist approach
## Find MLE of alpha and beta
gamma.log.likelihood <- function(alpha,beta,dat=data){
  n <- length(dat)
  fac1 <- n*alpha*log(beta)
  fac2 <- -n*lgamma(alpha)
  fac3 <- (alpha-1)*sum(sapply(dat,log))
  fac4 <- -beta*sum(dat)
  return(fac1+fac2+fac3+fac4)
}
neg.gamma.log.likelihood <- function(theta){
  return(-gamma.log.likelihood(theta[1], theta[2]))
}
gamma.logLikeRatio <- function(theta, mle){
  l.tilde <- gamma.log.likelihood(mle[1], mle[2])
  l <- gamma.log.likelihood(theta[1], theta[2])
  return(2*(l.tilde-l))
}
theta.hat <- optim(c(1,1), neg.gamma.log.likelihood)$par # the MLE

### Use MetropolisHastings algorithm to sample from the posterior
## Modified Code from 1.8-Gamma_Inference
inv.fisher.inf <- function(x = NULL, shape = NULL, scale = NULL) {
    n = length(x)
    val = matrix(0, ncol = 2, nrow = 2)
    val[1, 1] = n * trigamma(shape)
    val[2, 2] = n * shape/scale^2
    val[1, 2] = n/scale
    val[2, 1] = n/scale
    return(solve(val))
}
inv.Fisher.alpha <- inv.fisher.inf(data,theta.hat[1],theta.hat[2])[1,1]
inv.Fisher.beta <- inv.fisher.inf(data,theta.hat[1],theta.hat[2])[2,2]

## MCMC
MCMC.posterior <- function(alpha.0, beta.0, len, y){
  # alpha.0 is the initial value for alpha
  # beta.0 is the initial value for beta
  # len is the length of the random walk
  # y is the sample data 
  n <- length(y)
  prod.y <- prod(y)
  sum.y <- sum(y)
  alpha <- numeric(len)
  beta <- numeric(len)
  alpha[1] <- alpha.0
  beta[1] <- beta.0
  for (i in 2:len){
    alpha.old <- alpha[i-1]
    beta.old <- beta[i-1]
    # update alpha
    alpha.new <- rnorm(1, theta.hat[1], sqrt(inv.Fisher.alpha))
    if (alpha.new <= 0){ # exclude negative value
      alpha[i] <- alpha.old
    } else{
      fac.top.1 <- (n*alpha.new*log(beta.old)) - (n*log(gamma(alpha.new)))
      fac.bottom.1 <- (n*alpha.old*log(beta.old)) - (n*log(gamma(alpha.old)))
      fac.1 <- fac.top.1-fac.bottom.1
      fac.top.2 <- alpha.new*log(prod.y)
      fac.bottom.2 <- alpha.old*log(prod.y)
      fac.2 <- fac.top.2-fac.bottom.2
      fac.top.3 <- -0.5*(alpha.new^2 + ((alpha.old-theta.hat[1])^2)/inv.Fisher.alpha)
      fac.bottom.3 <- -0.5*(alpha.old^2 + ((alpha.new-theta.hat[1])^2)/inv.Fisher.alpha)
      fac.3 <- fac.top.3-fac.bottom.3
      p.alpha <- exp(fac.1+fac.2+fac.3)
      if (runif(1) <= p.alpha){
        alpha[i] <- alpha.new
      }else{
        alpha[i] <- alpha.old
      }
    }
    # update beta
    alpha.new <- alpha[i]
    beta.new <- rnorm(1, theta.hat[2],sqrt(inv.Fisher.beta))
    if (beta.new <= 0){ # exclude negative value
      beta[i] <- beta.old
    } else{
      fac.b.top.1 <- (n*alpha.new)*log(beta.new)
      fac.b.bottom.1 <- (n*alpha.new)*log(beta.old)
      fac.b.1 <- fac.b.top.1-fac.b.bottom.1
      fac.b.top.2 <- -((beta.new^2)/2 + (beta.new*sum.y)+((beta.old-theta.hat[2])^2)/(2*inv.Fisher.beta))
      fac.b.bottom.2 <- -((beta.old^2)/2 + (beta.old*sum.y)+((beta.new-theta.hat[2])^2)/(2*inv.Fisher.beta))
      fac.b.2 <- fac.b.top.2-fac.b.bottom.2
      p.beta <- exp(fac.b.1+fac.b.2)
      if (runif(1) <= p.beta){
        beta[i] <- beta.new
      }else{
        beta[i] <- beta.old
      }
    }
  }
  return(cbind(alpha,beta))
}
## Run the MCMC
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
walk <- MCMC.posterior(11, 20, 10000, data)
walk.alpha <- walk[,1]
walk.beta <- walk[,2]
plot(walk.alpha, type = "l", col = "chocolate", ylab = expression(alpha), xlab = "iteration",
     main = expression(Random~Walk:~alpha))
plot(walk.beta, type = "l", col = "cyan3", ylab = expression(alpha), xlab = "iteration",
     main = expression(Random~Walk:~beta))
